    <prp:abstract>Magnetic fields are found to be aligned with striations, channeling 
material from the outside onto the surface of filaments. Large-scale
sub-millimeter dust polarization observations - probing the denser inner
regions of filaments - tend to find filaments that are perpendicular
to the filament longer axis. OMC-3 is a textbook case of a filament 
with several embedded cores along its major axis with a very uniform
field perpendicular to it. Here, on the filament scale, the magnetic field
dominates over turbulence, and gravity can initiate contraction along 
the field lines. How does this relative significance between these
3 constituents change toward the core scale?
The science goals of this proposal are: (1) image the magnetic field 
morphologies in a sample of 7 dense cores and compare their average
field orientations with the large-scale field orientation, and (2)
derive the field strengths in 7 cores to establish the scaling of
field strength versus density from filamentary to core scales, 
in order to probe magnetic flux removal processes.
In order to achieve this, we propose Band-3 1" dust continuum 
polarization observations.</prp:abstract>
